sec.p:
Sympatry within Marphysa appears to be common: four species were described in close proximity from Zanzibar (
Crossland 1903 ) and three species from the Florida Keys, USA ( Treadwell 1911 , 1917 ). In the present study we found M. fauchaldi n. sp. , and M. mossambica to co-occur in soft substrates of Darwin Harbour (in one sample collected at the same time and place), and M. mullawa and M. mossambica , to cooccur in close proximity in the Kimberley region. Reasons for sympatry can be many, but in the case of this group, we suggest that two factors may be important: 1 . habitat partitioning—in the Florida Keys example M. viridis Treadwell, 1917 and M. nobilis Treadwell, 1917 were both reported from soft substrates, but M. fragilis Treadwell, 1911 was reported from crevices in rocky shores; and 2 . reproductive isolation as a result of larval developmental differences—some species have adopted methods for reducing larval dispersal either by having a short pelagic phase (e.g., M. sanguinea ;
Prevedelli et al.2007 ) or in the case of the Teretiusculagroup, encapsulating embryos and larvae in a jelly cocoon. The latter factor is also likely to be an adaptation for life in unstable environments such as soft substrates of coasts and estuaries where most of these species live. Further research in this area would be fruitful.
